  "local_port": 51834,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I format my memory card using cmd?",
  "response": "Formatting a memory card using the Command Prompt (CMD) in Windows is a straightforward process. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you format your memory card:\n\n### Step 1: Prepare Your System\n1. **Insert the Memory Card**: Insert the memory card into your computer\u2019s card reader or SD card slot.\n2. **Backup Data**: Ensure you have backed up any important data on the memory card, as formatting will erase all data.\n\n### Step 2: Open Command Prompt\n1. **Open CMD**:\n   - Press `Win + S`, type `cmd`, and press `Enter`.\n   - Alternatively, press `Win + R`, type `cmd`, and press `Enter`.\n\n2. **Run as Administrator**:\n   - Right-click on the Command Prompt icon and select **Run as administrator**.\n\n### Step 3: Identify the Memory Card\n1. **List Disks**:\n   - In the Command Prompt, type the following command and press `Enter`:\n     ```cmd\n     diskpart\n     ```\n   - Next, type:\n     ```cmd\n     list disk\n     ```\n   - This will display a list of all disks connected to your computer.\n\n2. **Identify the Memory Card**:\n   - Look for the disk that matches the size of your memory card. **Be very careful** to select the correct disk, as formatting the wrong disk will result in data loss.\n\n### Step 4: Select and Format the Memory Card\n1. **Select the Disk**:\n   - Type the following command, replacing `X` with the disk number of your memory card (e.g., `disk 1`), and press `Enter`:\n     ```cmd\n     select disk X\n     ```\n\n2. **Clean the Disk** (Optional):\n   - If you want to completely erase the memory card (recommended), type the following command and press `Enter`:\n     ```cmd\n     clean\n     ```\n   - This will remove all partitions and data from the disk.\n\n3. **Create a Primary Partition**:\n   - Type the following command and press `Enter`:\n     ```cmd\n     create partition primary\n     ```\n\n4. **Format the Disk**:\n   - To format the memory card, type the following command, replacing `FS` with the desired file system (e.g., `FAT32`, `NTFS`, or `exFAT`), and press `Enter`:\n     ```cmd\n     format fs=FS quick\n     ```\n   - Use the `quick` option for a faster format, or omit it for a full format.\n\n### Step 5: Assign a Drive Letter\n1. **Assign a Letter**:\n   - To make the memory card accessible, assign a drive letter by typing the following command and pressing `Enter`:\n     ```cmd\n     assign\n     ```\n\n### Step 6: Exit DiskPart\n1. **Exit**:\n   - Type the following command and press `Enter`:\n     ```cmd\n     exit\n     ```\n\n### Step 7: Verify the Format\n1. **Check in File Explorer**:\n   - Open File Explorer (`Win + E`) and verify that the memory card is formatted and accessible.\n\n### Notes:\n- **File System Options**:\n  - Use **FAT32** for compatibility with most devices, but it has a 4GB file size limit.\n  - Use **NTFS** for Windows systems with no file size limit.\n  - Use **exFAT** for compatibility with modern devices and no file size limit.\n\n- **Be Careful**: Always double-check the disk number to avoid formatting the wrong drive.\n\nThat\u2019s it! Your memory card is now formatted and ready to use.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
